P(slug="rise-of-indian-dj", date="2026-01-15", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="The rise of the Indian DJ: from wedding sets to world stages",
  excerpt="Homegrown selectors and producers are now global names. The story of India's own dance-music talent.",
  tags=["culture","DJ","India"],
  body="""<p>A decade ago, the biggest names on Indian line-ups were almost always imported. Today, homegrown DJs and producers headline festivals, tour internationally and top streaming charts. The rise of the Indian DJ is one of the great success stories of the country's music scene.</p>
<h2>From the ground up</h2>
<p>India's artists came up through every possible route — wedding and club circuits, bedroom production, underground collectives, and the festival main stages that gave them their first big crowds. What they share is a refusal to be treated as second billing to international acts. That confidence has reshaped the scene.</p>
<h2>A sound of their own</h2>
<p>The most exciting Indian artists aren't just imitating global trends — they're fusing them with Indian melody, classical elements, folk traditions and desi sensibilities to create something distinctive. That originality is what's earning them attention far beyond India's borders.</p>
<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>Every homegrown headliner makes the scene more sustainable and more self-assured. When local talent can carry a festival, the whole ecosystem — venues, promoters, crowds — grows stronger. India isn't just consuming global dance music anymore; it's producing its own stars.</p>""")

P(slug="women-in-indian-dance-scene", date="2026-01-19", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Women reshaping India's dance-music scene",
  excerpt="From the DJ booth to the promoter's desk, women are driving some of the most important work in Indian nightlife.",
  tags=["culture","women","India"],
  body="""<p>India's dance-music scene, like most around the world, has long been male-dominated — but that's changing, and some of the most vital work in the country's nightlife today is being led by women, on the decks and behind the scenes.</p>
<h2>Behind the booth and beyond</h2>
<p>A growing roster of women DJs and producers are earning festival slots and building devoted followings on the strength of their sound. Just as importantly, women are increasingly shaping the scene as promoters, event managers, artists and community-builders — the roles that actually determine what a night looks and feels like.</p>
<h2>Safer, better floors</h2>
<p>This shift matters beyond representation. A more diverse scene tends to be a safer, more welcoming one — and there's a real, growing focus across Indian nightlife on making dancefloors spaces where everyone can feel comfortable. That work benefits every single person who steps onto a floor.</p>
<h2>The direction</h2>
<p>The scene is healthier when the talent and the leadership reflect the whole crowd. The women driving India's nightlife forward are making it not just more equal, but genuinely better — and the momentum is only building.</p>""")

P(slug="the-promoter-collective-role", date="2026-01-27", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Behind every great night: what promoters and collectives actually do",
  excerpt="The unseen work that turns an empty venue into an unforgettable night. An appreciation of the people who build the party.",
  tags=["culture","promoter","India"],
  body="""<p>When a night goes perfectly, nobody thinks about the promoter — and that's the job done right. But behind every great party is a collective doing an enormous, invisible amount of work. Here's what actually goes into it.</p>
<h2>Curation is everything</h2>
<p>A promoter's most important skill is taste — choosing the right artist, the right sound, the right venue and the right crowd, then making them fit together. Anyone can book a DJ; building a coherent night that feels like something is an art.</p>
<h2>The logistics nobody sees</h2>
<p>Sound and lighting, licensing and permissions, security, ticketing, marketing, artist travel, cash flow, and a hundred tiny decisions about how a room should feel — the promoter carries all of it. When it works, it looks effortless. It never is.</p>
<h2>Building a community</h2>
<p>The best collectives — and we like to count ourselves among those trying — aren't just throwing events. They're building a community that trusts them, that shows up for the sound rather than just the headline, and that makes each night better by being there. That trust is earned one great party at a time.</p>
<p>So next time a night is perfect, spare a thought for the people who made it look easy.</p>""")

P(slug="nightlife-and-indian-weddings", date="2026-02-05", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="The wedding-nightlife crossover: how India's biggest parties went pro",
  excerpt="Indian weddings are among the world's great parties — and they've quietly transformed the events industry.",
  tags=["culture","weddings","India"],
  body="""<p>You can't talk about India's party economy without talking about weddings. Indian weddings are among the most elaborate celebrations on earth, and their scale has quietly professionalised the entire events industry — with real spillover into nightlife.</p>
<h2>The great training ground</h2>
<p>The sangeet, the cocktail night, the after-party — modern Indian weddings are effectively multi-day music festivals, complete with DJs, live acts, production and choreography. They've created a huge market for event professionals, sound and lighting companies, and performers, raising the standard of what a "party" means across the board.</p>
<h2>Destination weddings and the venues</h2>
<p>Cities like Udaipur and Jaipur built world-class event infrastructure largely on the back of the destination-wedding boom — and that same infrastructure (lakeside venues, resorts, production capacity) is exactly what makes them great for nightlife events too. The wedding economy paved the road the party scene now drives on.</p>
<h2>The overlap</h2>
<p>Many of the country's best DJs cut their teeth on the wedding circuit, and many venues do both. The line between "wedding entertainment" and "nightlife" is blurrier than you'd think — and India's love of a proper celebration underpins all of it.</p>""")

P(slug="sundowner-culture-india", date="2026-04-11", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="The rise of the sundowner: India's favourite way to start the night",
  excerpt="Golden light, easy music and a drink in hand — how the sunset session became a nightlife staple.",
  tags=["culture","sundowner","India"],
  body="""<p>Not every great music moment happens after midnight. The sundowner — the sunset session that eases you from day into night — has become one of India's most beloved nightlife formats, and it's easy to see why.</p>
<h2>The appeal</h2>
<p>A sundowner is low-commitment and high-reward: great music, golden-hour light, a relaxed crowd, and a drink in hand as the sun goes down. The soundtrack leans warm and melodic — deep house, afro house, downtempo — perfectly matched to the mood of the hour. It's accessible in a way a 2am club night isn't, pulling a broader, more mixed crowd.</p>
<h2>Where it thrives</h2>
<p>Rooftop bars, beach clubs, poolside decks and lakeside venues are the natural homes of the sundowner. Cities with a view — Goa's coast, Udaipur's lakes, the metros' skylines — have made it a signature. It also works beautifully as the opening act to a bigger night.</p>
<h2>The takeaway</h2>
<p>The sundowner proves that nightlife isn't only about the peak-time hours. Sometimes the best moment of the whole night is watching the sun drop with the right track playing. It's civilised, it's gorgeous, and it's very India.</p>""")

P(slug="microbrewery-music-culture", date="2026-02-21", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Craft beer and live beats: India's microbrewery music culture",
  excerpt="How the microbrewery boom quietly became one of India's most important live-music platforms.",
  tags=["culture","craft beer","live music","India"],
  body="""<p>One of the most significant developments in Indian nightlife over the last decade didn't come from a club or a festival — it came from craft beer. The microbrewery boom, led by cities like Bengaluru and Pune, created an entirely new kind of going-out culture that put live music at its centre.</p>
<h2>The format</h2>
<p>The gastro-brewery — great craft beer, solid food, and live music or a DJ, all under one roof — turned out to be a perfect model for India. It's casual, social and accessible, welcoming a crowd that might never go to a club but happily spends an evening with a pint and a band. Many of these venues have become vital platforms for local live acts.</p>
<h2>Why it matters</h2>
<p>Microbreweries gave independent musicians something the scene badly needed: regular, paying gigs in front of real crowds. They've nurtured local talent, broadened the audience for live music, and made "going out" less about the exclusive club and more about the accessible neighbourhood spot.</p>
<h2>The read</h2>
<p>It's a quieter revolution than the festival boom, but arguably just as important. The microbrewery is where a huge slice of India first discovered that a great night out could revolve around live music.</p>""")

P(slug="nightlife-tourism-india", date="2026-04-25", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Nightlife tourism: how the party became a reason to travel",
  excerpt="From Goa's beaches to Rajasthan's lakes, India's parties are pulling travellers. Inside the rise of nightlife tourism.",
  tags=["culture","tourism","travel","India"],
  body="""<p>Increasingly, people don't just party where they live — they travel for it. Nightlife tourism, where the event itself is the reason for the trip, has become a real force in India, reshaping how cities think about their party scenes.</p>
<h2>The destinations</h2>
<p>Goa has always drawn travellers for its beaches and its sunrise culture, and the year-end festival surge is a national migration. But the model has spread: boutique festivals in Rajasthan's forts and deserts, camping events in the hills, and lakeside parties in cities like Udaipur are all pulling people who fly in specifically for the experience.</p>
<h2>The stay-and-party model</h2>
<p>Smart venues have caught on, bundling accommodation with events — the destination-party weekend. It's a natural fit for cities with strong hospitality infrastructure, and it turns a single night into a whole trip (and a much bigger economic story for the city).</p>
<h2>Why it works</h2>
<p>A party in an extraordinary setting — a fort, a beach, a lakeside — is worth travelling for in a way a standard club night isn't. As India's scene matures, the events that combine great music with a great destination are the ones winning. It's exactly the model we've built Pronite around.</p>""")

P(slug="social-media-and-nightlife", date="2026-05-15", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="How Instagram rewired the way India parties",
  excerpt="Discovery, hype, FOMO and the guest list — social media has transformed nightlife. A look at the double-edged shift.",
  tags=["culture","social media","India"],
  body="""<p>You can't understand modern Indian nightlife without understanding social media. Instagram in particular has completely rewired how parties are discovered, marketed and experienced — for better and, sometimes, for worse.</p>
<h2>The upside</h2>
<p>Social media democratised discovery. A great collective no longer needs a marketing budget to reach a crowd — a strong Instagram presence, good content and word of mouth can fill a room. It's how underground scenes grow, how promoters build community, and how party-goers find nights that match their taste. Our own guest list runs on exactly this: Instagram and WhatsApp doing what expensive advertising used to.</p>
<h2>The double edge</h2>
<p>But the phone-in-the-air culture has a cost. Nights experienced through a screen aren't fully lived, and the pressure to capture content can pull people out of the moment. Some of the best venues and events now actively encourage a "phones down" ethos to protect the vibe.</p>
<h2>The balance</h2>
<p>The tools are here to stay, and used well they're brilliant for building a scene. The trick — for promoters and party-goers alike — is to let social media bring people to the dancefloor, then let the dancefloor be the thing that actually matters.</p>""")

P(slug="regional-scenes-rising-india", date="2026-05-27", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="Beyond the metros: India's regional scenes are rising",
  excerpt="The best nights aren't only in Mumbai and Delhi anymore. How smaller cities are building world-class party scenes.",
  tags=["culture","regional","India"],
  body="""<p>For years, the story of Indian nightlife was a story of four or five big cities. That's changing fast. Across the country, smaller cities and regional scenes are building distinctive, high-quality party cultures of their own — and reshaping the map.</p>
<h2>The new players</h2>
<p>Udaipur, with its lakes and resort infrastructure, has become a genuine destination for boutique, scenic events. Pune hosts one of the country's biggest festivals. Hyderabad's scene is booming on the back of its tech economy. The Northeast has some of India's richest live-music culture. Chandigarh drives North India's commercial floors. None of these are "the metros" — and all of them matter.</p>
<h2>Why it's happening</h2>
<p>Rising incomes, better venues, returning talent, and social media that lets a regional collective reach a national audience have all combined to make world-class nights possible outside the big four. Local promoters who know their city and crowd are building scenes tailored to their strengths.</p>
<h2>The Pronite view</h2>
<p>We're proof of it. A collective built in Udaipur, collaborating with national festival brands and drawing people from across the country to a lakeside in Rajasthan — that simply wouldn't have been possible a decade ago. The future of Indian nightlife is more spread out, more diverse, and more exciting than ever.</p>""")

P(slug="economics-of-a-club-night", date="2026-06-07", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="What actually pays for your night out: the economics of a club night",
  excerpt="Artist fees, venue costs, bar margins and ticket math — a look under the hood of how a party makes (or loses) money.",
  tags=["culture","business","India"],
  body="""<p>Ever wondered how a party actually works as a business? Behind the music and the lights is a genuinely tricky economic puzzle, and understanding it explains a lot about why nights are priced and run the way they are.</p>
<h2>The costs</h2>
<p>A single event carries serious expenses: the artist fee (the big one for headline shows), venue hire or revenue share, sound and lighting, security, licensing and permissions, marketing, and staffing. For a touring international act, travel and hospitality pile on top. The bill adds up fast, and it's all spent before a single ticket is sold.</p>
<h2>Where the money comes from</h2>
<p>Revenue flows from two main taps: entry (tickets and cover) and the bar. At many venues the bar is the real engine — which is why drink pricing works the way it does, and why table bookings with minimum spends matter so much to a venue's bottom line.</p>
<h2>The tightrope</h2>
<p>Promoters walk a fine line: price too high and the room's empty, too low and you lose money even on a packed floor. A sold-out night doesn't automatically mean profit. It's why guest lists, presales and community matter — filling the room early and reliably is what makes the whole thing viable.</p>
<p>Next time you're out, know that a lot of careful math made that carefree night possible.</p>""")

P(slug="pool-party-format-india", date="2026-04-15", cat="Scene Report", city="India",
  title="How the pool party became India's favourite summer format",
  excerpt="Daytime, water, sunshine and music — the pool party's rise is one of the defining trends of Indian nightlife.",
  tags=["culture","pool party","summer","India"],
  body="""<p>The pool party has gone from occasional novelty to one of the defining formats of Indian nightlife, especially as the weather warms. Its rise says a lot about where the country's party culture is heading.</p>
<h2>Why it took off</h2>
<p>The logic is simple and irresistible: India gets hot, and dancing in the sun with a way to cool off beats a stuffy club. The pool party turns the heat from an enemy into part of the fun. Add the daytime timing — more accessible, more social, friendlier to a mixed crowd — and you have a format with mass appeal.</p>
<h2>The Holi accelerant</h2>
<p>The modern colour-and-water Holi party supercharged the whole category, proving there was huge demand for produced daytime water events. That momentum now carries right through the summer, with rooftop pools, resort decks and lakeside venues running programming all season.</p>
<h2>The Pronite angle</h2>
<p>Our lakeside pool parties — Rangilo Rajasthan chief among them — are built for exactly this: a proper sound system, shaded chill zones, rain-dance cool-downs and a dancefloor you can wade into, all with the lake as a backdrop. The pool party isn't a gimmick; it's one of the smartest formats in Indian nightlife, and it's here to stay.</p>""")
